abstract: Biomass feedstocks (e.g., plant biomass, animal biomass, and municipal waste biomass) are processed to produce useful products, such as fuels. For example, systems are described that can convert feedstock materials to a sugar solution, which can then be fermented to produce a product such as a biofuel.
claims:
1. A method comprising:
wet milling a reduced recalcitrance lignocellulosic material.
2. The method of claim 1 wherein the recalcitrance of the lignocellulosic material has been reduced by irradiating the lignocellulosic material.
3. The method of claim 2 wherein irradiating comprises exposing the material to an electron beam.
4. The method of claim 2 wherein irradiating comprises delivering a dose of at least 5 Mrad to the lignocellulosic material.

5. The method of claim 1 wherein the lignocellulosic material is selected from the group consisting of wood, particle board, sawdust, agricultural waste, sewage, silage, grasses, rice hulls, bagasse, cotton, jute, hemp, flax, bamboo, sisal, abaca, straw, wheat straw, corn cobs, corn stover, switchgrass, alfalfa, hay, coconut hair, seaweed, algae, and mixtures thereof.
6. The method of claim 1 further comprising densifying the reduced recalcitrance lignocellulosic material prior to wet milling.
7. The method of claim 1 wherein wet milling is performed using a rotor/stator head.
8. The method of claim 7 wherein the rotor and stator include nesting rings of teeth.
9. The method of claim 8 wherein the stator comprises two or more concentric rings of teeth.
10. The method of claim 9 wherein the rotor comprises a ring of teeth configured to fit between adjacent rings of teeth of the stator.
11. The method of claim 7 wherein the clearance between the rotor and stator is from about 0.01 to 0.25 inches (0.25 to 6.4 mm).
12. The method of claim 8 wherein the spacing between the teeth in each ring of teeth is from about 0.1 to 0.3 inch (2.5 to 7.6 mm).
13. The method of claim 7 wherein wet milling is performed using a plurality of rotor/stator heads.
14. The method of claim 1 wherein wet milling is performed at a shear rate of from about 30,000 sec−1 to 50,000 sec−1.
15. The method of claim 1 wherein wet milling is performed in-line.
16. The method of claim 1 wherein a jet mixer is applied during wet milling.
17. The method of claim 1 further comprising adding an enzyme to the lignocellulosic material before, during or after wet milling.
18. The method of claim 17 further comprising adding a microorganism to the lignocellulosic material or a sugar derived from the lignocellulosic material.
19. The method of claim 18 wherein the microorganism is added after wet milling has been completed.

20. The method of claim 18 wherein the microorganism converts the lignocellulosic feedstock or sugar to a product selected from the group consisting of alcohols, organic acids, sugars, hydrocarbons, and mixtures thereof.
21. The method of claim 20 where a jet mixer is operated during conversion of the feedstock or sugar to the product.
22. A wet milling system comprising a wet mill disposed in a fluid having a biomass material dispersed therein.
23. The system of claim 22 wherein the biomass comprises a lignocellulosic material.
24. The system of claim 23 wherein the recalcitrance of the lignocellulosic material has been reduced by irradiating the lignocellulosic material.
25. The system of claim 24 wherein irradiating comprises exposing the material to an electron beam.
26. The system of claim 22 further comprising a jet mixer disposed in the fluid.
27. The system of claim 22 wherein the wet mill comprises a rotor/stator head.
28. The system of claim 27 wherein the rotor and stator include nesting rings of teeth.
29. The system of claim 28 wherein the stator comprises two or more concentric rings of teeth.
30. The system of claim 28 wherein the wet mill comprises a rotor/stator head.
31. A system comprising a tank, a jet head and a wet mill.
32. The system of claim 30 wherein the jet head and wet mill are disposed within the tank.
